The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Chennai, Dec. 27 (PTI): Madras High Court has directed authorities to compensate a petitioner who was fired because he was suffering from dementia, and has imposed a Rs 5,000 fine on two government officials.          
	The judges ruled that evidence suggests that C. Narayanan, an office assistant, had been sacked not because of misconduct, as was claimed, but because of his mental condition.                  
	Jaisalmer (PTI): A sword has been stolen from Jaisalmers royal collection. A police official said the 19th century artefact was reported missing yesterday from the museum at Sonar Quila, where it had been on display. Security cameras at the fort had not been working, he said.                   
	Ghaziabad (PTI): A train bound for Varanasi rammed into an autorickshaw on Sunday afternoon when it was trying to cross a railway track in Kallugari, Uttar Pradesh. Railway sources said no one was injured in the incident, which occurred after the cable man did not close a traffic gate, letting the three-wheeler cross.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): Jet Airways has suspended four members of its cabin crew who were detained this month in Londons Heathrow airport for carrying more cigarettes than allowed under British customs rules. The airline said it was probing the matter.                   
	Dindigul (PTI): A woman has delivered a child, a week after being sent to a womens prison at Nilakottai, Tamil Nadu. A court has ordered an inquiry into why the 25-year-old woman was sent to prison in the last stage of her pregnancy.                   
	Srinagar (PTI): A nine-day-old baby has died at a hospital after doctors allegedly gave him a drug past its expiry date. The Jammu and Kashmir government formed a committee to investigate the incident at Lal Ded Maternity Hospital. The panel would submit its report within seven days.                                                                                                                                              
